Wisbech, Cambridgeshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","England":"Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1475–1575":"1475–1575","1450–1550":"1450–1550","1475–1595":"1475–1595","1500–1600":"1500–1600","1430–1500":"1430–1500","1430–1501":"1430–1501","1550":"1550","1450":"1450","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1575":"1575","1465":"1465","1475":"1475","Abt. 1500":"omkring 1500","1430":"1430","1595":"1595","1 Oct 1500":"1. oktober 1500","1549":"1549","Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England","Wisbech Castle, Cambridgeshire, England":"Wisbech, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1475–1575":"1475–1575","1450–1550":"1450–1550","1475–1595":"1475–1595","1500–1600":"1500–1600","1430–1500":"1430–1500","1430–1501":"1430–1501","1550":"1550","1450":"1450","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1575":"1575","1465":"1465","1475":"1475","Abt. 1500":"circa 1500","1430":"1430","1595":"1595","1 Oct 1500":"1 oktober 1500","1549":"1549","Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wisbech Castle, Cambridgeshire, England":"Wisbech, Cambridgeshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1475–1575":"1475–1575","1450–1550":"1450–1550","1475–1595":"1475–1595","1500–1600":"1500–1600","1430–1500":"1430–1500","1430–1501":"1430–1501","1550":"1550","1450":"1450","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1575":"1575","1465":"1465","1475":"1475","Abt. 1500":"about 1500","1430":"1430","1595":"1595","1 Oct 1500":"1 October 1500","1549":"1549","Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wisbech Castle, Cambridgeshire, England":"Wisbech, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Alcock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Alcok</i>, a pet form of any of the many medieval personal names beginning with <i>Al-</i>, especially <i>Alan</i> and <i>Alexander</i>. The Middle English hypocoristic suffix <i>-cok</i> (see   Cocke  ) was very commonly added to personal names in Middle English: compare for example   Hancock   and   Wilcock  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Allicock","meanings":["English: variant of   Alcock  ."]},{"name":"Allcock","meanings":["English: variant of   Alcock  ."]},{"name":"Cocke","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>cok</i> (Old English and Old French <i>coc</i>) ‘rooster’.","patronymic from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Cok</i>, of uncertain origin but perhaps derived from the word in 1 above."]},{"name":"Alcott","meanings":["English: ostensibly a topographic name from any of a large number of places called in Old English as ‘the old cottage’ (Old English <i>(e)ald</i> + <i>cot(e)</i>). In fact, however, it is generally an altered form of   Alcock  , in part at least for euphemistic reasons.","History: Louisa May Alcott (1832–88), author of <i>Little Women</i> (1869), was the daughter of Amos Bronson Alcott (1799–1888), who had changed the surname from <i>Alcox</i>. The family trace their descent from an Alcocke family who emigrated from England to MA with John Winthrop (see   Winthrop  ) in 1630."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":74,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":83,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":94,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Richard Alcock was born in 1475, in Beverley, Yorkshire, England, his father, John Alcock, Bishop of Rochester, was 45 and his mother, Agnes Wynslowe, was 45. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth Alcocke. He died in 1575, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 100."},"et":{"1475–1575":"1475–1575","1450–1550":"1450–1550","1475–1595":"1475–1595","1500–1600":"1500–1600","1430–1500":"1430–1500","1430–1501":"1430–1501","1550":"1550","1450":"1450","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1575":"1575","1465":"1465","1475":"1475","Abt. 1500":"umbes 1500","1430":"1430","1595":"1595","1 Oct 1500":"1. oktoober 1500","1549":"1549","Beverley, Yorkshire, England":"Beverley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Wisbech Castle, Cambridgeshire, England":"Wisbech, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1475–1575":"1475–1575","1450–1550":"1450–1550","1475–1595":"1475–1595","1500–1600":"1500–1600","1430–1500":"1430–1500","1430–1501":"1430–1501","1550":"1550","1450":"1450","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1600":"1600","1500":"1500","1575":"1575","1465":"1465","1475":"1475","Abt. 1500":"noin 1500","1430":"1430","1595":"1595","1 Oct 1500":"1. lokakuuta 1500","1